Leading and managing the workplace: The role of executive functions 
 
 
What attributes determine who will make a superior leader or manager? Organizational 
leaders must juggle multiple roles and duties, often simultaneously. They must make sound 
decisions, solve problems, develop new ideas, and engage with partners and clients. Reasonably, 
organizations devote much effort to selecting those who are intelligent, skilled, of good 
judgment, and are personable, and much research has investigated how these abilities and 
qualities predict job performance. However, as we argue in this article, this picture is 
insufficient. In response, we introduce a set of cognitive abilities that drive flexible thinking and 
attention, known as executive functions (very different from Barnard’s functions of the 
executive!). We argue that these executive functions matter for how well individuals, particularly 
those who must lead and manage others and work in attention taxing environments, perform.  
Organizational research has largely neglected these abilities, perhaps because these 
abilities are often incorrectly conflated with assessments of general intelligence, and perhaps 
because of misperceptions that they are impractical to assess in organizations. We aim to bridge 
this gap by illustrating how these executive functions are relevant to job performance beyond 
other aptitude assessments, and by discussing how assessments of executive functions can be 
implemented in organizations. Specifically, we elucidate how executive functions, and the 
associated control of attention, are relevant in positions that require responsive, accurate thinking 
in time-limited, novel, and ambiguous situations. Throughout, we explain with different 
organizational examples why the effective management of attention – beyond prevailing 
explanations of organizational behavior – is critical to different leadership and management 
roles. It is not the goal of this review to introduce a novel theoretical model of job performance, 
