nor is it an extensive review of the job performance literature. Rather, our goal is to integrate 
basic psychological developments with theory and research in management: we show how the 
extensive research behind executive functions can be applied to various managerial roles. 
In the following sections, we introduce much research on executive functions and the 
processes and behaviors they drive. This work has included a diverse range of populations: 
community samples of adults across the lifespan, undergraduate samples in controlled 
experimental settings, and clinical samples with ADHD. However, we do note that a paucity of 
this work has been conducted in ecologically valid settings with individuals who are leaders and 
managers. Hence, we acknowledge that much of our

## Key Findings
discussion about the relationships between 
executive functions and managerial behavior posits that these extant findings will generalize to 
leaders in organizational contexts. Our goal in this paper is to explicate the potential 
relationships and spur ideas for organizational investigation; however, many of these ideas 
require empirical testing in settings outside of the laboratory. Nevertheless, we see that applying 
the cumulative body of work in cognitive, social, and neuropsychology holds relevance and 
insight for organizational scholars and leaders, given our knowledge that executive functions are 
a stable, individual difference across various contexts. 
First, we explain what executive functions are and why they provide a distinct, added 
benefit beyond assessments of general intelligence. Second, in addition to skills and knowledge, 
