Author Biographies: 
 
Todd Chan (toddchan@umich.edu) is a doctoral candidate in social psychology at the University 
of Michigan. He studies how people respond and cope with feelings of rejection and 
loneliness, and how cognitive abilities underlie how people effectively navigate social 
situations.  
 
Iris Wang (imxwang@umich.edu) is a doctoral candidate in social psychology at the University 
of Michigan. She studies judgment and decision making as well as evolutionary perspectives 
on threat avoidance mechanisms, social relationships, and self-identity. 
 
Oscar Ybarra (oybarra@umich.edu) is Professor of Psychology and Management and 
Organizations at the University of Michigan, and Faculty Associate at the Research Center 
for Group Dynamics at the Institute for Social Research. He studies the social underpinnings 
of cognition, how people navigate their relationships, and the need to balance connecting 
socially with the pursuit of personally valued goals. 
