28
been paid to how executive functions can influence negotiations. Here, we outline how executive 
functions enable successful negotiating skills, and how this perspective can inform whom in an 
organization is best suited to negotiate. Negotiations involve key tasks that do not just depend on 
intelligent reasoning: perspective taking, suppressing egocentric needs, emotion regulation, 
metacognitive regulation, and seeking joint outcomes. Ultimately, these tasks depend on both (a) 
sustained attention on another party’s perspective, and (b) being able to jointly represent in one’s 
attention multiple interests and perspectives simultaneously. Executive functions underlie both of 
these attentional abilities.  
Perspective Taking. First, navigating a negotiation requires taking the perspective of 
one’s negotiating partner and making accurate inferences about their intentions. This 
perspective-taking entails holding, representing, and comparing the viewpoints of other people 
with one’s own, which inhibition and working memory underlie (M. L. Meyer & Lieberman, 
2015 ; Wardlow, 2013 ; Ybarra & Winkielman, 2012). Individuals with better perspective taking 
are better able to judge the intentions of their negotiating partner. In turn, they are more likely to 
find and agree on joint and integrative outcomes (Galinsky, Maddux, Gilin, & White, 2008 ; 
Kim, Cundiff, & Choi, 2015). 
Emotion Regulation. Second, negotiating often requires being able to effectively regulate 
one’s emotions to stay “cool” in hot moments, and suppressing one’s egocentric needs (e.g., not 
interrupting to allow one’s partner to adequately respond) in favor of finding outcomes favorable 
to all parties involved. Indeed, individuals who are better at regulating their emotions (e.g., 
staying calm) and those who can strategically put on positive emotions are more likely to obtain 
concessions from their negotiating partner, and are more likely to have a continuing business 
relationship as one of their negotiated outcomes (Kopelman, Rosette, & Thompson, 2006). The 
