29
ability to regulate one’s emotions depends heavily on working memory and inhibition 
(Schmeichel & Tang, 2015). For example, individuals with low working memory ability are less 
able to suppress their initial, angry reactions when given negative social feedback (Hofmann, 
Gschwendner, Friese, Wiers, & Schmitt, 2008). 
Metacognitive Evaluation. Third, a dynamic negotiation requires accurate self-evaluation 
and the tracking of one’s performance. For example, to determine whether one’s strategy is 
working or requires change, individuals must evaluate how they are doing (e.g., “Am I doing 
well?”) relative to their negotiation partners (e.g., “Is what I am asking for realistic?”). 
Negotiators who have more realistic views of their own abilities (vs. overconfidence) and 
possible negotiation outcomes, and who are less egocentric, are more likely to come to an 
agreement with other parties (Dreu, Nauta, & Vliert, 1995 ; Thompson & Loewenstein, 1992). 
Having executive control of attention, which in particular working memory and inhibition 
underlie, facilitate accurate self-evaluation and the tracking of one’s performance in social 
situations, perhaps because one must represent all aspects of the situation to accurately evaluate 
oneself (Fernandez-Duque et al., 2000 ; Fleming & Dolan, 2014). Accordingly, individuals with 
ADHD show less accurate self-evaluations, attributable to their impairments in working memory 
(T. Chan & Martinussen, 2016 ; McQuade et al., 2011 ; Prevatt et al., 2010).  
Seeking Outcomes. Fourth, although many negotiations involve joint or integrative 
outcomes that can benefit all parties, looking for these integrative outcomes is an effortful 
process. A default, but fallacious assumption in a negotiation is that there must be a “winner” 
that emerges, or that one’s negotiating partner is exclusively adversarial (Bazerman et al., 2000). 
This type of thinking may blind individuals from seeing or seeking integrative gains that can 
benefit all parties in a negotiation and may hamper efforts at cooperation (Fukuno & Ohbuchi, 
