30
1997 ; W. Liu, Liu, & Zhang, 2015). Similarly, initial impressions of others’ personality and 
intentions are usually made automatically, but can often be wrong, especially when negative 
(e.g., that the other person only cares about themselves; impressions based on stereotypes) 
(Ybarra, 2002). Not correcting these initial impressions can often lead to inaccurate judgments 
and poorer negotiation outcomes. Accordingly, inhibition is required to counter automatic 
thinking with more informed judgments (Radvansky, Copeland, & Hippel, 2010). Thus, those 
with stronger executive functions should be able to expand the options for success.  
Strategic Concealment. Fifth, many negotiations necessitate the concealment of 
privileged information from the other party. Concealing information, especially in contexts that 
are already cognitively taxing, is a very cognitively demanding task on attention, one that 
requires sharp executive functions (Gombos, 2006 ; G. Visu-Petra, Varga, Miclea, & Visu-Petra, 
2013). Thus, executive functions may bolster success in ensuring that information detrimental to 
one’s own success in the negotiation is not compromised. 
Importantly, although intelligent reasoners can make a negotiation plan that aims to 
predict goals and outcomes, this is insufficient when negotiations depend on carrying out that 
plan adaptively and responsively with another party. Likewise, having skills and knowledge 
(e.g., “negotiation strategies”) are insufficient to carry out an effective negotiation. To illustrate, 
experimental studies show that when individuals are directed in the use of a “social skill,” in this 
case, being explicitly told to suppress a negative reaction because such a reaction would be rude 
towards another person present in the room, inhibition and switching abilities nonetheless predict 
individuals’ ability to do so (Hippel & Gonsalkorale, 2005). Thus, executive functions are 
required to carry out these behaviors successfully – especially when attention is taxed and there 
is not the luxury of time to deliberate or conduct extensive planning. 
