Implications. For organizations, our perspective suggests that keeping in mind the 
executive functioning ability of negotiators that represent an organization may confer better 
outcomes. More broadly, taking into account individuals’ executive functions may inform who 
may be best suited to staff positions generally requiring difficult or taxing business interactions. 
For example, when dealing with difficult partners or clients, employees often have to perform 
emotional labor, which means supplanting one’s authentic emotions with ones that are favorable 
to the organization’s goals (Grandey & Gabriel, 2015). Performing this emotional labor requires 
cognitive effort, perspective taking, and emotional regulation, of which working memory and 
inhibition underlie (Ybarra, Kross, & Sanchez-Burks, 2014). Given that how well employees 
carry out emotional labor affects how clients evaluate their performance (Groth, Hennig-Thurau, 
& Walsh, 2009), individuals with higher executive functioning may be particularly well 
equipped to effectively manage an organization’s negative or difficult relationships.  
Future Research. For scholars, we have highlighted several different pathways why 
individuals with higher executive functioning may be more effective negotiators. However, we 
encourage future research to further explore the mediating pathways between executive 
functioning ability and successful negotiation outcomes. For example, it is possible that 
individuals with higher executive functioning are also perceived as more powerful, given their 
ability to respond quickly and adaptively to another person. In turn, this perception may predict 
an increased ability to elicit concessions from their negotiating partner. As well, future work may 
also wish to investigate whether executive functioning ability can directly predict individuals’ 
ability to conceal certain privileged information in a negotiation from an opposing party under 
both cognitively taxing and non-taxing circumstances. Researchers may wish to examine these 
processes in simulated negotiations where negotiators’ executive functions are also assessed.  
