Change Behaviors 
Innovation 
 
To this point, we have discussed how executive functions facilitate how effectively 
individuals respond to time-limited, dynamic situations that require high levels of accurate 
performance. Now, we turn to a situation that is not necessarily time-limited or immediate, but 
still requires developing novel, creative insight into problems where there are no clear, ideal 
solutions. These contexts nevertheless strongly recruit executive functions. We illustrate how 
executive functions may help managers better generate innovative ideas and set strategic plans. 
Innovation is inherently developing novel strategies and ideas in response to situations. 
Of course, individual creativity – often driven by those in senior management – is the 
undercurrent of organizational innovation (see Amabile & Pratt, 2016). Accordingly, 
organizations strive to hire those who possess a tendency to think in novel or creative ways and 
aim to foster a corporate culture that fosters innovation. For example, organizations may wish to 
hire individuals who are open to new experiences and unconventional (Puryear, Kettler, & Rinn, 
2017). Yet, organizations often neglect the fact that individuals still require cognitive resources 
to generate creative ideas. From the present perspective, inhibition, working memory, and 
shifting are critical building blocks for being creative.  
First, being able to see links among different ideas and concepts requires overcoming 
initial, practiced, or established solutions. Inhibitory abilities are needed to resist the intuitive 
appeal of conventional solutions, and shifting abilities are needed to shift to a different mental set 
(Diamond, 2013 ; Fischer & Hommel, 2012 ; Nijstad, De Dreu, Rietzschel, & Baas, 2010 ; 
Zabelina & Robinson, 2010). Second, further to inhibiting conventional ideas, generating 
creative links requires the adaptive management of attention. On the one hand, when generating 
