33
new ideas, individuals must persist to find novel solutions. On the other hand, sustained attention 
can at times hinder creativity, as individuals need to be able to represent and shift among a flock 
of possible solutions and see how they may work together holistically rather than narrowly 
focusing on any one of them (Takeuchi et al., 2011). However, whether sustained or shifting 
attention is the goal, shifting and working memory abilities are required to represent possibilities 
and manipulate links among them (Chuderski & Jastrzębski, 2018).  
Accordingly, much evidence shows that beyond general intelligence, higher executive 
functioning ability predicts originality and fluency on both divergent and convergent thinking 
tasks (Benedek, Jauk, Sommer, Arendasy, & Neubauer, 2014 ; De Dreu, Nijstad, Baas, Wolsink, 
& Roskes, 2012 ; C. S. Lee & Therriault, 2013). Tasks of divergent thinking ask individuals to 
generate as many uses for an object (e.g., a brick) as possible (Kaufman, Plucker, & Baer, 2008); 
tasks of convergent thinking ask individuals to generate novel links among seemingly unrelated 
concepts (e.g., paint, doll, cat) (Mednick, 1968). In both cases, individuals must take new 
perspectives in solving problems rather than relying on established mental sets or solutions. 
Higher inhibitory and shifting abilities are associated with more creative performance on these 
tasks, meaning that individuals with sharper executive functions can see unique possibilities or 
unconventional solutions beyond those typically generated (Benedek et al., 2014 ; Gilhooly, 
Fioratou, Anthony, & Wynn, 2007 ; Zabelina, Robinson, Council, & Bresin, 2012). Higher 
working memory ability is also associated with better performance on convergent thinking tasks 
and other “insight” problems, because individuals are better able to simultaneously represent and 
combine relevant information (Chuderski & Jastrzębski, 2018) 
Implications. Of course, our perspective does not posit that executive functions are the 
only important predictor of whether creative or innovative thinking occurs. For example, 
