34
organizations also need to foster a climate of inclusivity, cooperation, and trust to provide a 
psychologically safe environment for individuals to develop creative ideas (Edmondson, Kramer, 
& Cook, 2004 ; Kessel, Kratzer, & Schultz, 2012). However, this framework does suggest that, 
beyond hiring unconventional and intelligent individuals, assigning tasks that require insight and 
innovation to individuals with sharp executive functions may improve an organization’s capacity 
to develop novel ideas. 
As well, many organizations spend considerable resources on creativity training 
programs, which teach employees skills that facilitate creative thinking (Gundry, Kickul, & 
Prather, 1994 ; Scott, Leritz, & Mumford, 2004 ; Smith, 1998 ; Tan, 1998). There is mixed 
support for these programs on their ability to improve creative outcomes, in part because these 
strategies are often not used in practice (Birdi, 2016 ; Klijn & Tomic, 2010 ; Scott et al., 2004). 
From our executive functioning perspective, these programs, which confer strategies and tools 
for creativity, may need to be supplemented with skill training that promotes directing attention 
towards generating and connecting ideas, to allow these creative strategies to be implemented. 
Indeed, organizations seeking to maintain or to be more innovative may wish to also consider 
focusing on training that strengthens the attentional abilities of employees, which may confer 
direct benefits on employees’ ability to generate innovative solutions to organizational problems. 
Future Research. For scholars, we urge future research to more closely examine how 
executive functions interact with creative training program outcomes. We propose that executive 
functions may interact with these programs in two ways. First, research has suggested that 
training may be more effective for those who are predisposed for creative thinking (e.g., through 
differences in personality and motivation) (Amabile & Pratt, 2016 ; Kandler et al., 2016 ; 
Woodman, Sawyer, & Griffin, 1993). We extend this notion by suggesting that the best 
