candidates for these programs may be those who already have high executive functioning 
abilities, who are able to stay directed and integrate multiple ideas and links efficiently when 
they are also equipped with the appropriate creative skills. 
Second, we see that many of these creative training techniques may in part rely on 
executive functions (Scott et al., 2004; Smith, 1998). For example, “habit-breaking strategies” 
challenge people’s assumptions and encourage people to change their perspective on a problem. 
“Relation-seeking strategies” encourage people to make novel connections between ideas. Both 
of these types of strategies rely on inhibition, working memory, and shifting to inhibit automatic 
assumptions, shift towards new perspectives, and represent relationships and links efficiently. In 
turn, this raises the possibility that executive functioning training (to be discussed in a 
subsequent section of this paper) may confer advantages for how individuals generate creative 
ideas. We encourage organizational scholars to examine questions like these. 
Implications for Managerial Selection 
We have detailed numerous ways in which executive functions have an impact on 
managerial performance. Throughout, we have discussed executive functions as an individual 
difference: those with higher executive functioning ability are thought to better master these 
workplace tasks given their high reliance on the executive control of attention. Thus, 
organizations should assess inhibition, working memory, and shifting. Although organizations 
are eager to use cognitive testing and assessment centers (Eurich, Krause, Cigularov, & 
Thornton, 2009), it is surprising that executive functions are seldom assessed in employee 
selection programs.  
As we have detailed, the ability to inhibit, direct, and allocate one’s attention is neither 
synonymous nor replaceable with measures of general intelligence or job-knowledge. To the 
