36
extent that we have demonstrated that these abilities are relevant to job performance in 
managerial roles or in other attention-taxing contexts, we strongly push for organizations and 
research to leverage the assessment of these abilities for employee selection and promotion.  
On the one hand, we recognize that these assessments may seem detached from job 
demands, and thus perhaps unappealing for organizations to implement (Highhouse, 2015). 
Likewise, measures that do not appear face valid are associated with decreased favorability 
among job candidates, and these negative perceptions may extend to overall evaluations of an 
organization, deterring candidates from applying (Hausknecht, Day, & Thomas, 2004). In fact, if 
unfavorable perceptions lead to low motivation, they may result in lower test scores on these 
tests (D. Chan, Schmitt, DeShon, Clause, & Delbridge, 1997). 
On the other hand, these concerns must be balanced with the fact that identifying talent 
through cognitive assessments is most predictive of job performance (Ployhart, 2006 ; Terpstra 
& Rozell, 1993). Further, not recognizing or retaining talent (e.g., through pay raises or 
promotions) may result in greater costs for an organization. To illustrate, managers and 
executives with higher cognitive ability, over and beyond a variety of job-related factors, are 
more likely to engage in job search while employed (Boudreau, Boswell, Judge, & Bretz, 2001). 
In our view then, accurately assessing executive functions is critical to ensuring that talent is 
recognized and retained within an organization. For example, assessing these abilities may help 
identify appropriate candidates for leadership development programs in an organization.  
We note that other cognitive assessments, like those to assess fluid intelligence, are 
widely used and accepted as part of job selection procedures by organizations and job 
candidates, and cognitive assessments are already perceived more favorably by job candidates 
than also widely used assessments of personality and honesty (Anderson, Salgado, & Hülsheger, 
