37
2010 ; Hausknecht et al., 2004 ; Murphy, Cronin, & Tam, 2003). Thus, we do not anticipate a 
different type of cognitive assessment – that of attention – to result in poor acceptance by 
organizations and managers familiar with the fact that cognitive abilities drive various important 
job outcomes. Further, as previously discussed, unlike reasoning assessments, executive 
functioning assessments have task demands that are simple and easily learned, and it is 
immediately clear to the test taker whether their responses are correct (e.g., it is clear that they 
responded incorrectly when they fail to inhibit a pre-potent response). In these ways, executive 
functioning assessments have advantages in providing immediate feedback and in being concrete 
and transparent, which are strengths for improving favorability and perceptions of fairness in 
selection procedures (D. Chan, Schmitt, Sacco, & DeShon, 1998 ; Gilliland, 1994 ; Truxillo, 
Bauer, Campion, & Paronto, 2002).  
Nonetheless, we see benefits in applying previous work on making cognitive testing more 
palatable on executive functioning assessments. To address issues of perceived low face validity 
(i.e., a surface view that test demands are detached from job demands), it may be helpful to 
briefly but transparently provide pre-test information about the nature of attention to explain why 
these tasks are being administered: research shows that these core abilities underlie how 
effectively people make decisions and perform in dynamic job situations, as demonstrated by the 
several examples in this paper. As well, providing pre-test information (e.g., format of the test, 
test-taking tips, and sample questions) has been shown to reduce these negative perceptions 
without affecting performance on the actual assessment (Burns, Siers, & Christiansen, 2008). 
Providing an explanation or justification of the tasks and the outcomes has been shown to bolster 
perceptions of evaluative fairness (Truxillo, Bodner, Bertolino, Bauer, & Yonce, 2009). Of 
course, we do not propose only measuring executive functions; organizations should consider 
