executive functioning assessment as one arm of multiple strategies of assessment (see Ployhart, 
2006). 
Although many of the existing instruments are designed to assess executive functioning 
in clinical and research populations, assessments of inhibition, working memory, and shifting 
can be readily adapted for organizational use (see Conway et al., 2005 ; Leary, 2007). Tests of 
working memory, for example, do not take more time or testing resources than tests of matrix 
reasoning (Raven, 2000), which are already often used in organizational testing. In this paper, we 
have described several examples of tasks that are used to measure inhibition, working memory, 
and shifting abilities. All of these tests can be self-administered on a computer in a short time 
span (Redick et al., 2012), and research shows that for cognitive abilities, conducting remote, 
mobile assessments in a non-proctored environment does not produce differences than when 
taken in a traditional assessment center (Castillo & Doe, 2017). As a starting point, looking at 
how health industries have rapidly adapted comprehensive assessments of executive functioning 
that can be completed on a tablet may provide directions for organizations (see H. Lee et al., 
2012 ; Weintraub et al., 2013).2 Assessments like these have incorporated the tasks that we 
previously have discussed, in a format that has been shown to be user friendly yet standardized 
and valid for individuals aged 3 to 85 years of age (Weintraub et al., 2013). 
Nevertheless, we encourage organizational researchers to further investigate and develop 
measures of executive functioning that are practicable and convenient for organizations to 
implement. As well, further organizational research that incorporates and compares assessments 
of fluid intelligence with measures of executive functioning, particularly the aspects unrelated to 
                                               
