Exercising Executive Functions 
Throughout, we have conceptualized executive functions as an individual difference. 
While these differences certainly exist, executive functions – and the associated control of 
attention – is also to an extent a flexible ability that fluctuates within individuals. Notably, 
executive functioning abilities can be hampered by fatigue or getting insufficient sleep the 
previous night (Boonstra, Stins, Daffertshofer, & Beek, 2007 ; Honn, Hinson, Whitney, & Van 
Dongen, 2018 ; Nilsson et al., 2005). These fluctuations are important to take into account, as 
they may directly impair workplace performance. For example, recent research suggests that 
nightly variation in sleep efficiency predicts how well entrepreneurs solve novel problems and 
generate creative ideas (Weinberger, Wach, Stephan, & Wegge, 2018). Similarly, as 
continuously managing one’s attention is an effortful process, executive functions can be 
exhausted over the course of the workday. For example, extended overtime work results in both 
a perceived and objective decrease in productivity and an increased risk of errors, due to a 
decrease in individuals’ abilities to regulate their attention (Hanna et al., 2005; Keller, 2009; 
Shimizu et al., 2004). 
However, that executive functions are flexible also means that they can be, to an extent, 
“sharpened” within individuals. Recent research, including meta-analyses, have shown that 
computerized cognitive training programs that have individuals practice working memory, 
shifting, and inhibition skills can confer gains on these abilities that last several months (Chiu et 
al., 2018 ; Kelly et al., 2014 ; Lampit, Hallock, & Valenzuela, 2014 ; Spencer-Smith & 
Klingberg, 2015). Thus, organizations concerned with the sharpening of executive functions may 
