40
benefit from implementation of these individual training programs for their leaders or managers. 
Of note, however, recent research has also shown that these working memory training programs 
are most helpful for those who already have high executive functioning abilities, and so selection 
remains important (Foster et al., 2017). Accordingly, this training may be more so conceived as 
the exercising or “maintenance” of executive functions rather than strengthening abilities that are 
weak to start.  
Scholars may wish to leverage study designs that examine day-to-day fluctuation in 
executive functioning and their impacts on managerial behaviors. As well, future research may 
wish to examine whether these executive functioning training programs lead to noticeable 
improvements in the managerial roles that we have discussed. In particular, research is needed to 
examine how frequently these training exercises need to take place to keep executive functioning 
adequately exercised in the workplace.

## Clinical Significance
Conclusions 
 
Our goal in this paper was to show why executive functions have high relevance for 
leaders, managers, or executives who must manage multiple roles in dynamic, time-limited or 
other attention-taxing contexts. Going forward, we urge organizational researchers to develop a 
greater focus on considering and assessing executive functions, and how these abilities predict 
how effective individuals are at fulfilling important functions of the organization. 
 
 
